    <item>
      <title>City of Stairs</title>
      <link>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/02/16/city-of-stairs/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 16 Feb 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/02/16/city-of-stairs/</guid>
      <description>&lt;figure class=&#34;cover-image&#34;&gt;
                &lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;20174424&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20174424.city-of-stairs&#34;&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://blog.jverkamp.com/embeds/books/city-of-stairs.jpg&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The city knows. It remembers. Its past is written in its bones, though the past now speaks in silences.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;20174424&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20174424.city-of-stairs&#34;&gt;City of Stairs&lt;/a&gt; is a wonderful book. The start is remarkably dense, dropping you into the deep end of a complicated world with flavors I at least wasn&amp;rsquo;t as familiar with where Proper Nouns abound and the rules are uncertain&amp;ndash;even to those living therein.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>The Boxcar Children</title>
      <link>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/02/15/the-boxcar-children/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 15 Feb 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/02/15/the-boxcar-children/</guid>
      <description>&lt;figure class=&#34;cover-image&#34;&gt;
                &lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;297249&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/297249.the-boxcar-children&#34;&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://blog.jverkamp.com/embeds/books/the-boxcar-children.jpg&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Many years ago, my mother would read aloud the Boxcar Children books to my brother and I. We read many many books together for many years, but the Boxcar Children are perhaps the ones I remember most. Now, perhaps it&amp;rsquo;s time to start passing that along to my own children.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From a child&amp;rsquo;s perspective, it&amp;rsquo;s a wonderful little book. The children are on a grand adventure, escapism idealized. They work together to not only survive but thrive without any adults telling them what to do. They get to make their own house in the woods and have a dog and everything ends up all right in the end.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
